caption: My girlfriend and I visited this restaurant as part of a three-day dining spree for the weekend. We were pretty excited to try something a little more upscale, but the experience there was admittedly a bit lackluster.  The real mood killer was the service. For the sake of transparency, we had made reservations as was required during the COIVD-19 Pandemic and knew that we had to sit outside, but the amount of time we waited to be served was enough to make a patient man tap his foot.  We and many other patrons were repeatedly asked if we wanted to drink something else than water, leading me to believe that expensive alcohol and thus, bigger tips were at the forefront of our server's mind rather than ensuring we had everything we needed. I think we spent more time waiting for us to be served and waiting for the check to be picked up than we did eating. On the bright side, the food was absolutely fantastic and my choice, the steak frites, was a generous portion and definitely worth the money.  I might give Brasserie Beck another chance on my next visit to D.C., I just wish we weren't treated as second-rate for not ordering rather pricey drinks.

Wonderful steak dinner for fiance and Fish for me Woine selection was perfect. Half price on Saturday evenings. The steak was cooked exactly to a medium rare (the way I like it) and was as tender as any I have had for a long time. Of course, the Frites on the side were exceptional as well. All of this wrapped with very good service and a sophisticated atmosphere.

Brasserie Beck is one of my family's all time favorites for a decade, but it had been a while since we had been there for dinner. It way exceeded our elevated expectations. The menu for New Year's Eve was interesting and diverse. One of us had the veal chop special, another had the duck special, and the third had the poached salmon. All were excellent, beautifully presented and we'll complemented by sauces and a vegetable or two. The eggplant and roasted carrots were perfect as sides. As usual, we had mussels, always perfectly prepared with a broth we would drink if it were not rude. The service was attentive and pleasant throughout. We had a great time, and will be making Brasserie Beck a more regular part of our rotation.

Private event - Great food and amazing service.  We hosted a private brunch for ~100 people at Brasserie Beck.  I could not offer a higher recommendation for the Brasserie Beck team.  Julie, the Director of Sales, is a star.  From the booking process to the actual event, I was impressed by the level of service and professionalism from her, her team, and the restaurant.  The event ran flawlessly, the food was great and the restaurant went above and beyond by altering some menu items to fit what we needed.  The private space (we reserved the back half of the restaurant) is perfect for a larger party event.  If you are searching for locations for larger private event, I highly recommend checking out Brasserie Beck.

The frites were excellent and there were three aioli choices- the Thai flavored one was yummy!!The egg skillet was great with crisp potatoes, onions and cheese and really good bread.  Hot chocolate was decadent and we had a cheesecake dessert- this was not exactly a cheesecake but whatever it was, it was delicious !!

Haven't been here almost since it opened over 10 years ago.  The reason I found out about it originally is because it is the same owner / chef as Marcel's (which is by far the best restaurant in DC).  I should have returned sooner.  Just finished a conference at the Convention Center and walked over.  Cool vibe, nice music and very nice bar which is where I sat.  Service is all over it and pleasent to all.  I had the happy hour oysters that were nice quality, plump ...  And they weren't $3 per!  Settled on the Moules Mediterranean (Goat cheese, Merguez Sausage, Harissa Ailoli w smoked Tomato Broth). Full portion with Frites.  Frites were fresh and delicious accompanied with house sauces that were very favorable.  The mixture of ingredients in Moules went together perfectly with plump Moules and a large amount of sausage.  I'm not an aficionado though to me this was the best Moules dish in DC I've had!  And filling.  Tons of beer available though I was not drinking.  I asked for non-alcoholic beer and was happy when a Erdinger was available as opposed to having an O'Douls or Heiniken zero shoves in front of me.  Honestly restaurants and bars are clueless on the number quality non-alcoholic beers that are available.  Glad I came back here and will definitely return with family, friends or business associates.  There's no way they 5 Stars though.  It's only by affiliation though with Marcel's that they lose out.  My 5 Stars goes to Marcel's!

The server didn't seem to know what to do when I asked for the tab and just...left. He eventually came back 5-10 minutes later and asked how we were doing, and I again asked for the tab and this time brought it.  Anyway, our issues are very difficult to capture in writing, and I am sure Brasserie Beck is a fine establishment. I'd go back for the mussels or a beer, but I hesitate to recommend the full dining experience.

AND if that’s not enough, these fries (frites, if you prefer) are the real deal—served with three different mayos. If you want some great Belgian food, this is the place to go! And to accompany any great Belgian meal, the beer list is a wonderfully comprehensive list of all of Belgium’s wonders. (Unconfirmed fun fact...they serve Antigoon, which is brewed especially for Brasserie Beck in Belgium.) One other thing...they make a really great espresso (and after living in Italy, I’m a tough critic on this one). You’ll see that all this praise is warranted...go try this gem!

The Belgian waffles (as a dessert dish to dinner) were among the best I’ve had; quite proper for a Belgian restaurant. The flavor of the waffles themselves was special amazing; I couldn’t describe why. The texture was very crispy with an extra “crunchiness” to it. The light and tart apple sauce at the bottom and the light vanilla sorbet on top completed the balance of this dish, making it not too overly sweet and complex. The other two dishes were of similar high quality ( lettuce salad with fresh green leaves and well-balanced sauce; short ribs with a wonderful red wine reduction and mild mustard sauce on top). The bread was super fresh. I thought this would be a business-y place with average food, but I was pleasantly surprised ! The service was not bad but just average (they came to refill wine but water was spilled all over when pouring; no pick up for bread crumbs; no renewal of silverware etc). I would love to come back again to try other dishes.:) i love running into hidden gem like this. Kudos to the chef!!! Thank you !!

Brasserie Beck. For being in downtown DC (a place where three star sit down restaurants reign), it's worthy of a four star rating. It's close to the Convention Center. Here's what's to love:  1) Space: It's not fine dining, but the design of the restaurant is approachable while also nice. It's massive with a large bar, dining area, and rooms for private events.  2) Patio: They have a great, large outdoor patio.  3) Drinks: They have one of the best beer programs in the city with beer you can only find here out of all places in DC.  4) Food: It's good. Nothing on the menu is unique, but their staples are excellent and I never tire of it.  If you are looking for a great spot for a working lunch, happy hour or event, go here!

We went in a 9:35 on a Tuesday night and got in right before they were planning on closing the kitchen. This did not stop the staff from being attentive and courteous, which is sometimes an issue when it is close to closing time.  The raclette appetizer was okay, but the main course and desserts (Amish chicken and boulet blanc; eclair and chocolate cake) were out of this world. Perfect portion sizes and plating. Their dessert wine was tasty, and the port selection was very good. My only complaint is the up-charge on their wine list, got a bottle I have often seen a my local store selling for $15.00 on their menu listed at $55.00. However, it was a birthday celebration, so we splurged on the wine.  In conclusion: Amazing food, great service, and only caveat is do research on their wine list before going to make sure you get "bang for your buck."
